---
title: "Ripples"
date: "2025-10-07"
category: "poem"
---

Tides break the surface of variegated rock, 
Trees bow, granting drops of unfallen leaves.

Mirrors in the ground, to them do crows flock,
Nesting on branches and underneath eaves.

Remnants of a storm, a tempest foregone,
Relics of what is no more, yet they persist.

Marks of arrows loosed and swords drawn,
Blind with war, and to a devil in their midst.

Ripples break the surface of the water,
Western light pours in, turning, reflecting.

Into the west, the sun grows hotter,
The ripples close in, churning, collecting.

Rays of light, orange and crimson,
Emerging stars foretell the night.

There lies the liquid he swims in,
On variegated rock, under unchanged light.

Ripples attempt, struggle, and fail,
Tides explode, fight, push, and flail,
The sea rises profoundly to no avail.

There is no cleansing the ocean in their flood,
Indeed, for there is no washing of their blood.
